article.headline: N. Iowa 73, Wis.-Milwaukee 66
article.story: MILWAUKEE (AP) -- Jordan Eglseder was just too big for Wisconsin-Milwaukee. The 7-foot-1 center scored a career-high 20 points and had 10 rebounds as Northern Iowa (4-0) defeated Wisconsin-Milwaukee 73-66 on Sunday. "He definitely got going and with his size it definitely discouraged us," Milwaukee coach Rob Jeter said. Jeter's team hit 35 percent of its shots and Northern Iowa had eight blocked shots, including three by Eglseder. Eglseder, whose previous career high was 16 points against Northern Illinois Nov. 9, was nearly unstoppable in the first half. He scored 14 points as he powered his team to a two-point lead by overpowering Milwaukee center Tim Flowers, a 6-foot-8 freshman. "Flowers played kind of on my back the whole game," Eglseder said. "Coach told me to take it right at him and I did." Wisconsin-Milwaukee (2-1) tied the score at 58 on a free throw by Ricky Franklin with 5:08 left to play. But Northern Iowa scored six straight points on baskets by Travis Brown, Eglseder and Jared Josten to take the lead back at 64-58. Eric Coleman, who added 12 points for Northern Iowa, said his team stayed cool and did what it had to down the stretch to win. "We battled for tough rebounds, we ran the floor and beat the press and hit shots," he said. Torre Johnson of Wisconsin-Milwaukee led all scorers with 29 points and Paige Paulsen had 11. Josten scored 16 points for Northern Iowa. Coleman defended Johnson most of the game and came away impressed by his opponent. "Torre is a tough player," Coleman said. "He was hitting from all over the place. He was single-handedly keeping them right in the game." But Northern Iowa tightened its defense on Johnson, who didn't score in the final eight minutes. "I think our guys did a good job of making him take tough shots," Northern Iowa coach Ben Jacobson said. Milwaukee led 18-14 after a Franklin basket but Northern ran off eight straight points starting with a 3-pointer by Eglseder to go ahead 22-18. Northern led 35-33 at halftime after Johnson hit a long 3-pointer at the buzzer. Despite the loss, Milwaukee has improved since last season, when it lost 11 of its first 13 games and finished 9-22. One missing ingredient is scoring from the guard spot -- no guard got more than five points against Northern Iowa. "We have to have a guard step up," Jeter said. The problem is connected to Avery Smith, who led all Milwaukee scorers with 15.5 points a year ago but was cut from the team before the first game for violating team rules. Jeter said he has good guards and someone will step up as a scorer.
